      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this course on AI governance in tech teams. We're going to start by looking at a challenge that's playing out right now across organisations of every size. AI tools are being adopted at a remarkable pace, and that's genuinely exciting. But here's the problem: the processes and policies that should guide how those tools are used are often struggling to keep up. When innovation moves faster than oversight, gaps appear, and those gaps aren't just theoretical concerns. They can lead to real consequences, whether that's data being handled inappropriately, decisions being made without proper accountability, or teams being exposed to risks they didn't even know existed. Good governance isn't about slowing things down or blocking progress. It's actually about protecting the people building these systems and the users who rely on them. So throughout this course, we'll be looking honestly at where those gaps tend to appear and what you can do about them."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So let's talk about what a governance gap actually looks like in practice. Imagine a team gets excited about a new AI tool, they start using it straight away, and nobody stops to ask whether there are any policies in place to guide that use. There probably aren't. And alongside that, nobody is quite sure who is responsible if something goes wrong. Security reviews get skipped because everyone is moving too fast, and the risks that are building up are often completely visible, sitting right there in the open, but nobody is paying attention to them. That is the core of the problem. When speed becomes the top priority, safety and oversight tend to get pushed to the back of the queue. And this is not about slowing innovation down for the sake of it. It is about recognising that when oversight is missing, even well-intentioned teams can end up in serious trouble without ever meaning to."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So let's look at where these governance gaps actually show up in practice. One of the most common patterns we see is developers quietly adopting AI tools on their own, often weeks or months before anyone in security or compliance even knows they exist. And when something does go wrong, there's frequently no clear person or team who owns that risk. Making things harder still, most existing policies were written long before large language models were even a concept, so they simply don't cover the situations teams are now facing. There's also a real problem around visibility. When AI is helping write code or informing decisions, the audit trail is often patchy or missing entirely, which creates serious headaches when you need to demonstrate accountability. And underpinning all of this is just the sheer speed of adoption. Compliance processes that were designed for slower, more deliberate change are constantly struggling to catch up. These are the gaps we need to understand before we can begin to address them."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "When teams start adopting AI tools without going through official channels, something called shadow IT begins to take hold. Essentially, people are using unapproved applications that the IT department simply doesn't know about. And that creates a whole set of hidden problems. Sensitive data might be flowing into these tools without anyone realising, which means potential leaks are happening completely under the radar. Because these tools aren't officially managed, there are no proper audit trails, so if something goes wrong, there's no record to investigate. From a compliance perspective, this is genuinely worrying, because regulatory gaps can pile up very quickly indeed. And perhaps most critically, your IT team loses its ability to see the full picture of what's happening across your systems. So what starts as a well-meaning attempt to work more efficiently can quietly become a serious security and governance risk. That's exactly why visibility and oversight matter so much from the very beginning."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "When employees start using AI tools that haven't been approved or reviewed by IT or security teams, you end up with what's often called shadow IT. And the risks here are very real. There's no record of what's being used or what data is being shared, which means sensitive information could be flowing into external platforms where you simply don't know how long that data is kept or who can access it. At the same time, compliance obligations can be quietly broken without anyone realising. Your security team may have no visibility into which tools are actually being used across the organisation, and that's a serious problem. Vulnerabilities start to build up faster than anyone can find them, let alone fix them. So the challenge isn't just about one rogue tool. It's about a pattern of ungoverned adoption that creates hidden risks across the whole organisation, often long before anyone notices something has gone wrong."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "When employees start using AI tools that haven't been approved by IT or security, you end up with what's commonly called shadow IT, and it creates some serious blind spots. Nobody knows what data is being entered into these external platforms, how long that data is being stored, or who might have access to it. That's a real problem when you consider obligations like GDPR or ISO 27001, because those rules don't pause just because someone found a convenient free tool online. Breaches can happen quietly, without anyone in the security team even knowing there's a threat to respond to. And here's the thing: there's no audit trail. No record of what was shared, when, or with whom. It only takes one unsanctioned tool used by one well-meaning employee to create an exposure that affects the whole organisation. This isn't about blame; it's about understanding why oversight matters before problems appear."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So now we know the risks, let's talk about what you can actually do about them. Bridging the governance gap doesn't have to be overwhelming, and you don't need to have everything sorted overnight. Start by finding out which AI tools your team is already using, because you might be surprised. Once you know what's in play, you can put some sensible guidelines in place around how those tools should and shouldn't be used. From there, make sure your people understand the risks we've been discussing, not to frighten them, but to help them make better decisions. It's also worth having one person who owns this area, someone who keeps an eye on things and acts as a point of contact. And importantly, this isn't a one-time exercise. AI is moving fast, so your governance approach needs to keep pace. Think of it as an ongoing habit rather than a box you tick once and forget about."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let's bring this all together. The core message here is simple: AI adoption moves fast, and governance almost always lags behind. When there are no clear policies in place, people do not stop using AI tools, they just make their own decisions about how to use them, and that is where the problems start. Shadow AI, data exposure, compliance risks, accountability gaps, these are not theoretical concerns, they are happening right now in organisations just like yours. The good news is that you do not need a perfect, fully formed governance strategy before you can act. Small, practical steps genuinely make a difference. An AI register, a basic usage policy, a simple review process, these are all achievable starting points. And the best place to begin is with an honest audit of what AI tools your team is already using. You might be surprised by what you find. From there, you can start building something that actually works."
        }
      ]
    }
